                     <interp inst="t18350302-837-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18350302-cd-136" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350302-837-offence-1 t18350302-cd-136"></join>4th of March</rs>, 1 spoon, value 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18350302-name-938" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-938" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-938" type="surname" value="GOLDING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-938" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350302-837-offence-1 t18350302-name-938"></join>Jeremiah Golding</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-939" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-939" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-939" type="surname" value="GOLDING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-939" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>JEREMIAH GOLDING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoemaker, and live in Church-street, Shore<lb></lb>ditch. The prisoner has been my apprentice nearly three years—on the 4th of March we missed a silver table-spoon from the kitchen—I inquired amongst the men for it—they all denied having seen it—I then sent a lad to search the water-closet—I was called down afterwards, and a man had the bowl of this spoon, and the tip of the handle was in a sand-bag, which he had in his hand—I received information in the evening that the prisoner had confessed that he sold the part of the handle to Mr. Pearson—I went there and found it—it corresponded with the other parts, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183503020160"></xptr>
               <p>formed the spoon I had missed—I asked the prisoner what he had sold it for—he said, "Two shillings"—I told him to get it, and he got it from under the counter—I gave him into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-940" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-940" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-940" type="surname" value="WATE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-940" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WATE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the prosecutor's employ. I found the bowl of the spoon, and the top of the handle.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350302-name-941" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-941" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-941" type="surname" value="PEARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350302-name-941" type="given" value="LAWRENCE"></interp>LAWRENCE PEARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a silversmith, and live in Shoreditch. I bought part of this spoon of the prisoner—he said he worked for his father in the dust-yard, and he sent him to sell it—he looked as if he came from a dust-yard—I gave him 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—it is worth about 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
